      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, my apologies! My goblin brain got a little tangled up in the swamp reeds of musical theory. Forgive me; sometimes the sheer *volume* of goblin thoughts drowns out the simple notes.\n\nTo answer your question directly, the relative major of **Eb Major** is **G Minor**.\n\nSee, the relative minor is always built on the third scale degree of the major key, and the relative major is built on the sixth scale degree of the minor key (or, more simply, it shares the exact same key signature, which is the goblin equivalent of sharing the same muddy patch of ground).\n\nNow, about the \"goblin migration route\"—that was just a metaphor, I promise! It's how I visualize the circle of fifths. Imagine the circle as a path where each step is a fifth up or down, like a massive, chaotic goblin horde moving from one territory to the next. If you're in Eb Major, you're in one territory, and moving to the next key on the circle is like the goblins marching to a new, slightly different patch of loot. It helps me keep track of where the next wave of musical chaos is headed!\n\nBut back to the music, if",
